Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset(1599X13) contains information of 1599 red-wines with 13 variables (“X”,“fixed.acidity”,“volatile.acidity”,“citric.acid”,“residual.sugar”, “chlorides”,“free.sulfur.dioxide”,“total.sulfur.dioxide”,“density”,“pH”, “sulphates”,“alcohol”,“quality).”x" is a count variable. “Quality is an ordered factor variable with lowest quality being 3 and heighest being 8.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I would really like to work out the relationahip between quality and alcohol content of red wines. Does higher quality red wines have higher alcohol content or not. Also the variation of pH with alcohol content.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

What holds the control over pH of red wines i.e. free.sulhur.dioxide, volatile.acidity, sulphates or alcoho. Also, variation of parameters in quality 5 and 6(most counts). What features have strong co-relations. And, variation of density with quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No, I didn’t create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset. But, I converted quality into 3 groups i.e. 3-5, 5-7,7-9. And, grouped parameters by quality and then summarised parameters in the quality group (5-7).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the

form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I used log scale and sqrt scale in univariate plots to obtain somewhat normal distribution.

breaks <- c( 3,4,6,9 )
df$quality.group <-cut(df$quality,breaks)
quality_group<-group_by(df,quality.group)
df.group <-summarise(quality_group,mean_alcohol =mean(alcohol),mean_pH= mean(pH),
                     mean_fixed.acidity= mean(fixed.acidity),
                     mean_volatile.acidity= mean(volatile.acidity),
                     mean_density= mean(density),n= n())

Reflection

The dataset contains information of about 1599 redwines with 13 variables to represent its characteristics. Mostly parameters followed somewhat normal distribution. Mostly redwines in the data belong to quality 5& 6. I studied the relationship b/w quality of red wines and its various parameters and relationship b/w various parameters. Lastly, I summarised the data into three quality groups. The quality of redwines was correlated with alcohol content and volatile acidity. Also, I assumed that pH would be controlled by alcohol content, but to my surprise pH was correalted to citric acid and fixed acidity. Not to forget, alcohol content and density were related too.

I struggled with multivariate analysis. It was bit difficult to use three-four variables to use at the same time to draw plots. But, a little research here and there worked finally.Also, it being my very first experience in R, it was a great experience exploring functions.

Using the insights from correlation coefficients provided by the paired plots, it was interesting exploring quality using density plots with a different color for each quality. Once I had this plotted it was interesting to build up the multivariate scatter plots to visualize the relationship of different variables with quality by also varying the point size, using density plots on the x and y axis, and also using density plots.

A next step would be to develop a statistical model to predict red wine quality based on the data in this dataset.
